An ancient stromalite contains blue-green algae that have been extinct for over half a billion years ago. Accretion appears to have been geologically altered since it first formed. Sticker has number "2" printed on it.
exhlabel3: An ancient stromalite contains blue-green algae that have been extinct for over half a billion years ago. Accretion appears to have been geologically altered since it first formed. Sticker has number "2" printed on it.

descrip: Bifurcated geode encasing a three dimensional (horsetail?) leaf. Some structural details present on the negative impression. Sticker label reads "24". Edit (KE, 11/23): Siderite concretion not "bifurcated geode" (not a valid term). Mazon Creek Assemblage
dimnotes: Dimensions taken while holding both halves together.

descrip: Fern impression and leaves scattered in a black siltstone. Primary fern is approximately 4 centimeters in length. Likely carbonized.
Fern impression in an irregularly shaped black siltstone. At least two different plants present. Likely carbonized.
Extinct "scale tree" genus encased in a tan sandstone. Only needles are preserved. Pennsylvanian.

Slab of black siltstone preserves an unidentified branch and bark impression. Both sides of slab contain fossils. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age. Tammo Reichgelt (UCONN) suggests the fossils look like reproductive organs.

Two 'coal' specimens preserving plant fossils. In smaller specimen, plant parts are scattered throughout the rock. Note(KE: 11/23): Tiverton rather than Triverton appearing on Google. According to RockD, Tiverton rocks are Pennsylvanian and part of the N
Well preserved impression of scale tree leaves in a black shale. On underside, more stems and leaves are preserved from same species.
exhlabel3: Well preserved impression of scale tree leaves in a black shale. On underside, more stems and leaves are preserved from same species.

descrip: Part of a stem from a fossil horsetail preserved in large piece of  black siltstone. Fossil difficult to discern. Note (KE: 11/23): Cromwell means either East Berlin or Portland Formations. Early Jurassic.
Fern parts preserved in shale-like rock. White markings show additonal structures on reverse. Likely carbonized.
Unidentified plant preserved in a small piece of tan siltstone. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age.
Hand-sized piece of anthracite coal has an approximately trapezoidal shape and is crumbling on one side.
Hand-sized piece of petrified wood. Mostly light brown color, but other earthy hues can be seen.
Black shale-like rock preserves remains from an ancient fern. Fern has reflective luster and underside has other fossils.

Single oxidized stem from an unknown plant preserved in a tan siltstone. Specimen is fragile. Edit (KE:11/23): This was previously catalogued as a Paleozoic plant. It is a Hartford Basin Fish: tail and small portion of body preserved. Mesozoic NOT Paleoz
Small fossil leaf impression on a shale like rock. Underside reveals another leaf of same color (reddish brown).

Irregularly shaped piece of  black siltstone encases faint fern leaf and stem impressions. Different plant embedded on underside (Lepidodendron?). 
Edit(KE, 11/23): ID'd as Sphenophyllum sp. by Tammo Reichgelt (UConn). Range of Devonian to Triassic.
Scale tree impression preserved in shale-like rock. Both sides of specimen have highly symmetrical bark impressions covering the entire surface.
Pale fern leaf contrasts with the dark grey siltstone matrix. Structure is highly visible. Underside preserves fainter remains. Likely carbonized.
Possible stem preserved in a light brown shale. Fossil takes up little space on the large slab.
Branch from an unidentified plant preserved in dark grey shale-like rock. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age.
Piece of dark grey shale preserves impression from scale tree leaf and stems. One edge of specimen is fractured in a straight line. Fine structural detail visible.

Various branches scattered throughout a light grey mudstone. Underside is smooth and eroded. Note (KE: 11/23): The Joggins Nova Scotia site is a fifteen million-year sequence of Late Carboniferous rock (nasa.gov).
Semi-circular petrified stem has been well worn and is smooth. Rock is light grey in color. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age.

Bark impression shows eight whole nodules in grey rock. Fragments of other nodules are also visible. 
Edit (KE: 11/23): This looks like Stigmaria. Not nodules. Root impressions. The little circles are where the root hairs would attach. (Univ. Kentucky).
Hand-sized specimen of petrified wood in various brown and grey hues.

Small portion of a branch from an unidentified plant. Parallel indentations preserve xylem or similar details. Note (KE: 11/23): The Joggins Nova Scotia site is a fifteen million-year sequence of Late Carboniferous rock (nasa.gov).

Various branches and plant parts embedded in a light grey sandstone-like rock. Bark impression also present. Underside preserves two additional branches. Note (KE: 11/23): The Joggins Nova Scotia site is a fifteen million-year sequence of Late Carbonifer
Large raindrop-shaped coprolite preserved in a dark gray shale. Crosswise indentations run the length of the fossil. Shale is very flat and roughly rectangular.

Four seed fern fossils; two preserved in fine-grained grey rock, two preserved in fined-grained tan rock. All are faint, but distinguishable. Note(KE; 12/23): Google says that rocks in this county are Devonian and Carboniferous and Neuropteris starts in

Three ferns preserved in three seperate bifurcated geodes. Are labelled "A", "B", and "C".Rock color is mostly light grey. All ferns exhibit bilateral symmetry. 
Note (KE: 11/23): Siderite concretions not "bifrucated geodes" (not a valid term). Mazon Cr
Series of parallel ridges denotes presence of plant stem embedded in a dark brown rock. Rock has uneven surface and has an irregular shape.

Three portions of colorful and unusually textured bark. Mostly light grey, but include orange, red and purple hues. Nodules from tree surface apparent. Largest piece is fragile. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age.

Plant stems and faint leaves preserved in half of a bifurcated geode of light tan color. Specimen has an elliptical shape. Note (KE;11/23): Siderite concretion not "bifurcated geode" (not a valid term). Mazon Creek assemblage. 309 Ma. Northeast Illinois.
Ancient horsetail relative preserved on one side of black slab of shale; ferns on underside. Impressions have reflective luster and a label reads "WF267".
exhlabel3: Ancient horsetail relative preserved on one side of black slab of shale; ferns on underside. Impressions have reflective luster and a label reads "WF267".

descrip: Two ferns in dark grey 'coal'. One contains half of a leaf and the other contains stems. Numbered with circlular  blue stickers labeled "1" and "2". Note(KE: 11/23): Tiverton rather than Triverton appearing on Google. According to RockD, Tiverton rocks a

Small silhouette of plant leaf or similar in a dark grey rock. Plant impression is darker than the surrounding matrix. Note (KE 11/23): This was previously catalogued as Paleozoic but know evidence for it.

Fossilized coniferous wood (Cupressinoxylon) in various brown hues. A series of parallel ridges is visible, suggesting a directional orientation for the fossil when it was alive. Note (KE, 2020): Likely phosphatized.
exhlabel3: Fossilized coniferous wood (Cupressinoxylon) in various brown hues. A series of parallel ridges is visible, suggesting a directional orientation for the fossil when it was alive. Likely phosphatized.

descrip: Tan and brown specimen of petrified algae containing striking bands of alternating color. Two sides are polished and smooth, revealing more intricate banding.
Leaf impression of an unknown fern species preserved in reflective brown mudstone. There is a discoloration of the rock surrounding the fossil fern.

Mostly light brown segment of petrified wood with lengthwise ridges that are parallel with each other. The sides of the specimen that were originally inside the trunk are smooth and lighter in color. Edit (KE: 11/23) This was previously catalogued as Pal

Possible faint plant impression in a brownish shale. All fossils are small and are near the edge of the rock matrix. Note (KE: 11/23): East Berlin means Early Jurassic NOT Paleozoic as was previously catalogued. Probably siltstone rather than shale.

Fossil fern leaf preserved in dark brown mudstone with reflective luster. Fern is well preserved: form and color are largely intact. Underside of specimen reveals a large fossil leaf. Unusual structures around the edges suggest that there are more fossil

Two specimens containing plant fossils (possibly ferns) embedded in black "coal". Mostly leaves and stems visible. Sticker labels read "A 36" (for the larger specimen) and "B 36" (for the smaller specimen). Note(KE: 11/23): According to RockD, Tiverton r

descrip: Stems (possibly from Lepidodendron) embedded in a dark grey siltstone. One edge of rock has distinctive reddish tint. Both sides of rock contain fossil plant impressions.Note(KE: 11/23): Need to confirm id to confirm age.
Stem of an unidentified plant  embedded in dark grey rock. Stem is characterized by diagonal and lengthwise indentations. likely carbonized. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age.
Lepidodendron or related species seen in picture; fern leaf impression on underside. Larger leaves are scattered throughout the dark grey matrix. Note(KE: 11/23): Need to further id to confirm age.
Small traces of plant stem preserved in a light grey siltstone. Fossil is visible as a dark silhouette in matrix.

Large leaf impression has three dimensional texture and shows good structural detail. Smaller stems and leaves also present. Rock is dark grey, reflective and gritty. Note(KE: 11/23): Tiverton rather than Triverton appearing on Google. According to RockD

Reflective siltstone preserves over a dozen fossil leaves on both sides of specimen. Fossils are in good condition, but are scattered. Likely carbonized.

Small dark grey rock contains leaf and stem impressions. Both sides of rock have impressions: Side A (shown in picture) has fern fossil and underside (Side B) has likely angiosperm leaf. Green sticker reads "A". Likely carbonized.
Small silhouette of plant stem preserved in gritty brown siltstone. Fossil takes up little space on rock matrix. Note (KE:11/23) This was previously catalogued as Paleozoic but know evidence for it.

Bifurcated geode of tan color preserves elongated fossil leaf. Sides of concretion are labeled "A" and "B" with circular blue stickers. Note (KE: 11/23): Siderite concretion, not "bifurcated geode" (not a valid term). Mazon Creek assemblage. 309 Ma. Nort

descrip: Hand-sized specimen of fossilized wood of tan and brown color. Specimen was likely from a large tree, given the negligible curvature of the part of the speciment that would have been the bark. Mineral deposit or replacement on one side.
Fern or seed fern impression in a sooty dark grey siltone. One edge of the rock has a prominent point. Likely carbonized.

Shale preserves one long stem on side label "A". Opposite side (labeled "B") has a smaller stem and perhaps a leaf. Note(KE: 11/23): Tiverton rather than Triverton appearing on Google. According to RockD, Tiverton rocks are Pennsylvanian and part of the

descrip: Black colored specimen of petrified wood. Inside of specimen has a chalky white color, visible on either end. A letter from Albert Purpura explaining some history of the specimen is included. Likely carbonized.
A smooth-edged leaf with a tapering point preseved in a brown matrix. Venation is visible, but faint.
Well preserved conifer needles embedded in a black shale-like rock. Needles have single vein and fossils overlap. Underside has been polished.
recfrom: Friends of Dinosaur State Park and Arboretum

descrip: Light brown leaf with venation embedded on a large, light grey slab of rock. A smaller leaf that is difficult to distinguish is also present. Slab has a very low weight compared to similarly sized specimens in shale.

Bifurcated geode with positive and negative leaf impressions on the inside. Leaf is dark colored compared to matrix and stickers reading "A" and "B" label each half. Note(KE: 11/23): concretion not "bifurcated geode" (not a valid term). This looks like s
dimnotes: Both halves were held together while measurements were taken.

descrip: Lepidodendron and calamites stem impressions in a slightly metamorphosed brown matrix. Underside also contains fossils. Label is present describing some of the details of the fossil.
Small fish fossil embedded in fine-grained tan matrix. Fish is preserved in excellent condition; very narrow bones can be seen.
exhlabel3: Small fish fossil embedded in fine-grained tan matrix. Fish is preserved in excellent condition; very narrow bones can be seen.

descrip: Large slab of black shale preserves dozens of fossil plants. Side shown in picture has a white film on the fossils; underside is reflective but has no white film. Fossils are mainly ferns.
Light grey specimen contains a small, elongated leaf with serrated edges. The rock has a very low density.
Small, crumbing piece of brown rock embeds a conifer branch and stem. Branch is on side with number "33" on a rectangular sticker; stem is on underside.
Unidentified leaf and branch embedded in a light grey shale-like rock.  Structural details on both branch and leaf are well preserved. It appears that the specimen was broken and glued back together.
White and green accretion of petrified algae. On the side that is polished, whorls are clearly visible. lower Bridger Formation.
Piece of shale-like rock containing wavy surface of bark. Has sparkling mineral on the surface of the impression. Color of specimen is dark grey.
exhlabel3: Piece of shale-like rock containing wavy surface of bark. Has sparkling mineral on the surface of the impression. Color of specimen is dark grey.

descrip: Two halves of a stem impression in a metamorphosed dark grey rock. Undersides of both halves contain many smaller plant impressions. Likely carbonized.
dimnotes: Both halves held together while measurements were taken.
exhlabel3: Two halves of a stem impression in a metamorphosed dark grey rock. Undersides of both halves contain many smaller plant impressions. Likely carbonized.

descrip: Hand-sized piece of irregularly shaped 'coal' preserves ancient fern impressions. Some ferns have a reflective luster. Underside contains additional fossils.
Small piece of mostly dark brown petrified wood. The wood was either bent while alive or distorted in the rock to create its present curvature. The specimen has a smooth surface.

Well preserved specimen of a fern similar to Pecopteris. Positive and negative fossils present. Fronds are perpendicular to the stem of the plant. Note (KE: 11/23): image and description don't match up. Mike Ross decided stick with description over image
One piece of brown petrified wood with holes on both ends. One side of the specimen is polished, revealing unusual patterns .

Biforcated geopde containing a seed fern with serrated leaflets. About 12 fronds are present. Note (KE: 11/23): Siderite concretion not "bifurcated geode" (not a valid term). Mazon Creek assemblage. 309 Ma.
exhlabel3: Concretion containing a seed fern with serrated leaflets. About 12 fronds are present.

descrip: Stem from a petrified horsetail, possibly Calamites. Lengthwise ridges are present around the circumference of the specimen. The horsetail is mostly dark brown in color. "WF 80" is written on the side.
Large rectagular slab of light grey petrified wood. Specimen has somewhat flaky texture and ring segments show little curvature. Patches of darker color are also present.

Fragmented, reflective stem impression visible on both sides of specimen. Matrix is fine grained shale and has powdery white substance on the surface.

Excellently preserved leaf embedded in dark grey sandstone. Venation and three dimensional structure present. Rectangular white sticker reads "146". Note (KE, 2021): Concretion. 113-93.9 Ma.
exhlabel3: Excellently preserved leaf embedded in dark grey sandstone. Venation and three dimensional structure present. Rectangular white sticker reads "146". Concretion.

descrip: Small, rectangular piece of petrified wood. Specimen is light brown and has relatively uniform color distribution.
Very small specimen contains faint plant impressions (likely leaves) in three dimensions. Rock is mostly dark grey and is very fine-grained. Red paint with black lettering reads "WF 15".
Hand-sized specimen of dark grey shale preserves leaves and stems. Side shown in picture has reflective coating on fossils and has a compound leaf. Underside contains fainter stems.

Well-preserved fern fossil embedded in a tan siltstone or similar. Specimen is an oval and approximates the shape of the fern within it. Red paint with black lettering reads "WF 22".  Edit (KE, 11/23): Siderite concretion. Mazon Creek Assemblage. 309 Ma.
exhlabel3: Well-preserved fern fossil embedded in a tan siltstone or similar. Specimen is an oval and approximates the shape of the fern within it. Red paint with black lettering reads "WF 22". About 309 Ma.

descrip: Dark grey shale with a different branch on either side. Rock is broken into two pieces and contains no fossils in the middle plane. Specimen has slight convex curvature.
exhlabel3: Dark grey shale with a different branch on either side. Rock is broken into two pieces and contains no fossils in the middle plane. Specimen has slight convex curvature.

descrip: Cylindrical portion of an unidentified plant stem. The surface around the circumference has fibrous structures aligned in approximately the same direction. The cross section has no rings, but tiny indents can be seen.
Reddish-brown specimen of petrified wood. Three of the six sides have been cut and polished. Yellowish streak radiate around a focal point on underside.
Dark grey shale encases contrasts striking orange leaf impressions from an extinct seed plant genus. Fossils are on the entire surface of the the matrix, but none are on underside.
habitat: Coolest of the warm climates in W. Aus., wet, coal swamps

descrip: Light grey specimen of petrified wood has slight curvature and uneven texture. Red paint with black lettering reads "WF 84".
Faded light brown specimen of petrified wood. Surfaced is rough; overall shape approximates a rectangular prism. Few distinctive features present.
Black and grey specimens of petrified wood have fragile structure. Black powder on surfaces gives specimen a gritty texture. Two of the pieces fit together.
Segment of petrified wood has smooth black mineral and rougher brown mineral in marble-like pattern.
Small, circular rock contains a leaf from a dicotyledon. Outline and venation visible. Stickers on underside read: "39" and "163". Note (KE): Possibly a concretion.
Piece of petrified wood composed of a multicolored agate. Mostly brown, but reddish hues are present. Underside contains sooty black crystals.
Specimen of petrified wood superficially looks quite similar to modern dried wood. The specimen is brown and sinewy. A label reads "16".
habitat: Coast of the Western Interior Seaway
site: Medicine Bow Mts/Citizens' Coal Mine, WY

descrip: Ripple marks preserved on large slab of reddish sandstone. Wavelength is approximately 1.5 cm. A portion of the slab has been broken; the ripple marks presumably extended beyond what is visible in the specimen. Likely Early Jurassic of CT.

Reddish sandstone preserves ripple marks and mud cracks from an ancient lake or similar. Wavelength is approximately 0.7 cm. Underside labels corners letters A through D. Number 14 is written in center. Likely Early Jurassic of CT.
Large section of tree trunk petrified into a reddish-brown sandstone. Cross-section shows no rings, but surface of specimen resembles living tree trunks.
Large slab of reddish sandstone preserves a three toed footprint, probably a theropod or other carnivorous dinosaur. Mudcracks present. Underside has number "394". Likely Late Triassic of CT
habitat: Large tropical rift valley: fluvian, lacustrine, floodplain

descrip: Reddish sandstone preserves dozens of raised folds from worms burrowing in mud. White substance dots surface of specimen.
Three-toed negative track impression in reddish sandstone, probably from a theropod or other small carnivorous dinosaur. Mudcracks present. Number "388" is written on underside.

Three-toed negative track impression in reddish sandstone, probably from a small theropod or other carnivorous dinosaur. Three distinctive mudcracks present. Many lustrous mineral grains in matrix. Underside has arrow drawn in white. Likely Early Jurassi
habitat: Large tropical rift valley: fluvian, lacustrine, floodplain

descrip: One very large slab of grey sandstone preserving positive footprint from a large theropod, probably Dilophosaurus. Claw impressions are visible at the end of each toe.

Five mica sheets of various sizes. All are light brown in color and are rather fragile.

Dark brown to grey goethite with a bubble-like appearance on the surface. Internal struture is fibrous and multicolored. White tag reads "259AK" and older label reads "19a" and the year (presumably) "1801".
Glassy datolite crystals arranged in small pea-sized clusters. Color is white to grey. Smaller dark grey goethite crystals also present.
Translucent quartz and datolite crystals form hand-sized aggregate rock. Crystal size is typically from 5 to 10 millimeters. Label reads "472" on underside.
Six fairly large twelve-sided crystals of almandine. Color is dark brown and two are encased in rock. One crystal is tagged with the number "54".
dimnotes: Dimensions taken from largest specimen, including rock that crystals are encased in.

descrip: Dark brown dravite prism with lengthwise striations. Broken end appears to have no distinct cleavage plane.
Large and very dense specimen of off-white barite with tabular crystals. Specks of black mineral fused to surface.
Many small pieces of dull black chalcocite atop light grey igneous rock. Numbers "2-080" and "295" are written on labels on underside.
Scaly, metallic specimen of muscovite approximates a cube. White rock (Quartz?) intrusion present. Number "14 " written on round label.
Fibrous grey crystals radiate from cental point at near bottom of specimen. Tremolite formed on top of white imestone base. Specimen is mounted on glass plate.
White barite and clear quartz crystals formed after hot magma in chamber cooled and solidified. Very large specimen.
1.1 billion year old gneiss specimen shows extensive metamorphisism. Banding present.
Igneous rock consisting of many minerals including: quartz, muscovite, biotite, staurolite, and garnet. Color and luster vary greatly.
Large portion of a petrified conifer trunk that has a dark brown color. No apparent rings or internal structure, but surface has texture similar to living tree trunk.
Igneous rock with of barite, sidenite, and chalcopyrite crystals. Color is mostly reddish-brown, but white, gold, and dark brown hues also present. Specimen is quite large.
Glass display case containing skull casts of archeaopteryx, velociraptor, and deinonychus, as well as claw casts from velociraptor and deinonychus.
dimnotes: Dimensions of display, not of fossil casts inside.

descrip: Two light grey hadrosaur eggs with cracks throughout specimens. One egg has bulbous protrusion. CT scans reveal that one of the eggs may have fossilized embryo remains. Late Cretaceous.
Dozens of small brachiopod fossil impressions preserved in a dark grey slab of sandstone. Some impressions show details of shells. Pennsylvania.
Cast of  American alligator skull including joints and teeth at various stages of development.

descrip: Standing skeleton of a Great Blue Heron held in place with wire, wood mount base. Modern animal.

descrip: Batrachopus. Probably made by small crocodilians. Late Triassic.

descrip: Trace fossil formed by crawling invertebrate arthropods.

caption: Negative Overprints
descrip: Obscured negative overprints. Probably footprint-maker unspecified.  Found in Newington, CT.

descrip: Anomoepus. Probably made by an early ornithiscian.

descrip: Antipus. Tracks and scratch marks were made by lizard-like animals, probably sphenodontids, related to modern Tuatara of New Zealand.

caption: Anomoepus
descrip: Anomoepus. Several different kinds of tracks present. Found in Turners Falls, Massachusetts. Very weathered.
habitat: Large tropical rift valley: fluvian, lacustrine, floodplain

caption: RIpple Marks
descrip: WIndblown ripple marks. Made approx. 200 million years ago in shallow water.

caption: Ornithiscian Dinosaur
descrip: Life-size model of an indeterminate beaked, herbivorous dinosaur from the early Jurassic. Name means "bird hip."

caption: Ornithiscian dinosaur
descrip: Life-size model of an indeterminate beaked, herbivorous dinosaur from the early Jurassic. Name means "bird hip."

caption: Anchisaurus model
descrip: Life-size model of an Anchisaurus. Anchisaurus was an herbivorous sauropodomorph, from the early Jurassic, originally thought to be a Prosauropod.

caption: Hypsognathus model
descrip: Life-size model of a Hypsognathus. Hypsognathus was a moderately-sized anapsid reptile, living in the late Triassic.

caption: Metoposaurus model
descrip: Life-size model of a Metoposaurus. Metoposaurus was a large amphibian with weak limbs and a flat head full of sharp teeth, and lived in the late Triassic.

caption: Rutiodon model
descrip: Life-size model of a Rutiodon. Rutiodon was a crododile-like, late Triassic phytosaur predator.

caption: Young Stegomus model
descrip: Life-size model of a young Stegomus. Stegomus was a small aetosaur, with several wide scutes on the body for protection.

caption: Dilophosaurus model
descrip: Life-size model of the park's mascot, Dilophosaurus. Dilophosaurus was an early Jurassic carnivorous theropod, and is thought to be the maker of the CT state fossil, Eubrontes.

caption: Anthophylite
descrip: Medium-sized sample of  Anthophylite with fibrous crystal patterns. Beige and brown with a vitreous luster.

caption: Stilbite
descrip: Large stilbite sample.

caption: Sphalerite + Milky Quartz
descrip: Sphalerite and milky quartz together in one sample. Sphalerite is dark grey and shiny, with a resinous luster. Milk quartz, which dominates the sample, is milk-white with a vitreous, greasy luster and white streak.

caption: Milky quartz
descrip: Large milky quartz sample with well-formed hexagonal, prismatic crystals. Milk-white color and vitreous, greasy luster.

caption: Stilbite + quartz
descrip: Rock filled with tiny stilbite and quartz crystals. Stilbite crystals are less numerous but larger, in yellowish prisms with resinous luster. Quartz is more abundant, in more craks, with smaller crystal formations. Clear to white in color and greasy/vitr

caption: Emerging Protoceratops statue
descrip: "Emerging" Protoceratops Andrewsi  bronze statue on a 6"x4"x4.5" wood base. Scale 1:2. By Doris Tischler, 1990. Marked with a #31.

caption: Ambushed statue
descrip: "Ambushed" bronze statue. Parasaurolophus Walkeri + Dromaeosaurus Albertensis. By Doris Tischler, 1982. Marked #31/50. Scale 1:50.

caption: Triceratops Prorsus statue
descrip: Bronze statue of Triceratops Prorsus. Scale 1:50. By Doris Tischler. Marked 31/50.

caption: Brachiosaurus Brancai statue
descrip: Bronze statue of Brachiosaurus Brancai. 1:50 Scale. By Doris Tischler, 1983. Marked 31/65.

caption: Battering Rams statue
descrip: "Battering Rams" bronze statue. Pachycephalosaurus Wyomingensis. 1:50 scale. by Doris Tischler, 1985. Marked 31/65.

caption: Double Header statue
descrip: "Double Header" bronze statue. Ankylosaurus Magniventris with Albertosaurus Lancensis. 1:50 scale. By Doris Tischler 1987.

caption: Amethyst points
descrip: Large chunk of amethyst points, ranging in size from about half an inch in diameter to over two and a half inches in diameter. Color ranges from a light purple to maroon. Greasy, vitreous luster.

caption: Iron Ore
descrip: Iron ore sample containing hematite, goethite, and limonite. Dark brown to rusty in color, portions are heavily oxidized.
site: Old Meramec Iron Mine, St. James, MO

caption: Iron Ore
descrip: Large iron ore chunk containing hematite, goethite, and limonite. Dark brown to rusty in color, portions are heavily oxidized.
site: Old Meramec Iron Mine, St. James, MO

caption: Tyrannosaurus Rex statue
descrip: Bronze statue of a Tyrannosaurus Rex. 1:50 scale. Marked 31/50. By Tom and Doris Tischler, 1979.

caption: Controntation statue
descrip: "Confrontation" bronze statue. Allosaurus Fragilis with Stegosaurus Stenops. 1:50 scale. By Doris Tischler, 1984. Marked 31/65

caption: Consummate Predator statue
descrip: "Consummate Predator" bronze statue. Dimetradon Grandis with Edaphosaurus Pogonias. Scale 1:50. By Doris Tischler, 1983. Marked 31/65

caption: Catcher Gets Caught statue
descrip: "Catcher Gets Caught" bronze statue. Tylosaurus Proriger with Pteranodon Ingens. 1:50 scale. By Doris Tischler, year not listed. Marked 31/50

caption: Going Fishing statue
descrip: "Going Fishing" bronze statue. Hydrotherasaurus Alexandrae. 1:50 scale. By Doris Tischler 1982.

caption: Clathropteris
descrip: Fossil of a Clathropteris frond fragment. Triassic fern.

caption: Otozamites
descrip: Fossil of Otozamites foliage. Triassic cycad.

caption: Equisetites
descrip: Fossil of an Equisetites stem, showing leafy nodes. Triassic horsetail.

caption: Semionotus
descrip: A preapred, robust specimen of Semionotus showing decay of skull and fins. Triassic fish.

caption: Semionotus
descrip: A distinctly curved Semionotus specimen. Fully prepared. Triassic fish.

caption: Semionotus
descrip: Near-perfect Semionotus fossil, fully-prepared on an uncut slab, from the Durham area. Triassic fish.

caption: Coprolite
descrip: Unusually large Coprolite specimen, tapered. Probably from Diplurus. Durham area.

caption: Diplurus
descrip: Large specimen of Diplurus, a coelacanth. Two or more feet long, showing parts of the internal skeleton.

caption: Human skull model
descrip: Model of a human skull. Labeled "Joe" on the front in marker, no other labels. Equipped with springs for the jaw and a hinge for the top of the skull.

caption: Sphenodon skull
descrip: Small skull of an unspecified member of the Sphenodon genus. Sphenodons are the only surviving members of the order Rhynchocephalia. Only two species exist in this genus, and both are commonly called tuataras. No other identification or labeling present.

caption: Coyote skull (female)
descrip: Female coyote skull. Marked #13. No other identification or labeling.

caption: Pitted quartz
descrip: Small sample of pitted quartz, in a rusty, iron-heavy bit of rock. Crystals are small, but developed. Vitreous in luster.
dimnotes:
Sample is less than an inch in almost any dimension and very thin.
1" cube box contains all crystals.

caption: Lepidolite + quartz
descrip: Baseball-sized rock containing sections of Lepidolite and quartz. Light brown to pearly in color. Several well-formed hexagonal crystals. Both are vitreous in luster.

caption: Quartz
descrip:
Large silicate rock with many small quartz crystals formed on one face. Crystals are fairly well formed, vitreous, colorless clear to opaque.

Originally id'd as quartz
Reidentified as calcite on marble by Fritz Moritz

caption: Smoky quartz
descrip: One large, baseball-sized smoky quart crystal. Bits of mica and quartz attached at some corners. Light to dark brown in color, vitreous in luster.

caption: Quartz
descrip: A large, softball-sized chunk of very well-formed, hexagonal dark yellow quartz. Smaller veins of quartz and mica throughout. Vitreous luster.

caption: Quartz
descrip: Golfball-sized chunk of rock with several large hexagonal quartz crystals. Smaller quartz crystals also appear. Crystals are vitreous and colorless.

caption: Quartz
descrip: Baseball-sized chunk of milky white quartz. Many crystals are well-formed and hexagonal, others are smaller and simple. Vitreous in luster.

caption: Quartz
descrip: Baseball-sized chunk of milky white quartz. Many large, well-formed hexagonal crystals, and numerous small, simpler crystals. Vitreous in luster.

caption: Feldspar
descrip: Chunk of feldspar about the size of a deck of cards. White and pale yellow in color. Marked "20". Vitreous luster.

caption: Beryl
descrip: Very small sample of one well-formed hexagonal prism crystal of beryl. Quartz surrounds the beryl in simple crystals. Beryl is yellow and vitreous. Mounted on a one-inch-by-one-inch piece of styrofoam.
dimnotes: Dimensions are all under one half of an inch.

caption: Albite
descrip: Small chunk of albite about the size of a quarter. Dense white microcrystals tightly concentrated. Vitreous luster.

caption: Cleavelandite
descrip: Two baseball-sized chunks of cleavelandite, a variation of albite. Flaky, solid white, plated crystals with right-angle cleavage and a vitreous luster.
dimnotes: Two samples are nearly the same dimensions. Second sample is about a half inch smaller in height than the dimension listed.

caption: Stilpnomelane
descrip: Four small samples of Stilpnomelane on calcite. Golden sections of stilpnomelane on clear calcite crystals. Luster is vitreous.

caption: Muscovite
descrip: Medium-sized chunk of muscovite mica. Characteristically thin, shiny plating. Pearly luster.

caption: Muscovite
descrip: Baseball-sized chunk of muscovite. Crystals are dark grey to white. Characteristically flaky, shiny, and pearly in luster.

caption: Fuschite
descrip: Three samples of the chromium-heavy variety of muscovite, fuschite. Samples vary in color from green to brown to white. Fuschite flakes are shiny, flat, and pearly in luster.
dimnotes:
Dimensions describe largest sample. Other two samples:
2) 1"x4"x2.25"
3) 1.25"x2.75"x1.5"

caption: Muscovite
descrip: Baseball-sized muscovite in an uncommon curved pattern. Pegmatite rock also contains quartz, mica, and feldspar. Pearly luster.

caption: Muscovite
descrip: A large sample of muscovite mica. Characteristically thin, plated crystal formations. Pearly luster.

caption: Muscovite
descrip: Large sample of muscovite mica. Characteristically thin, plated crystal formation. Pearly luster.

caption: Tourmaline
descrip: Small, thin sample of dark green tourmaline. Linear crystal formation with a vitreous luster.

caption: Prehnite
descrip: Several sections of well-formed, node-like prehnite crystals in a softball-sized chunk of basalt. Crystals are very pale green and vitreous in luster.
site: King Philip's Cove Talcott Mountain, CT

caption: Biotite + tourmaline
descrip: Baseball-sized chunk of biotite with tourmaline. Biotite crystals are dark, very linear in structure, and pearly in luster.

caption: Tremolite
descrip: Medium-sized rock dominated by tremolite. Crystal formation is linear and pointed. Crystals are grey to light brown in color, and vitreous in luster.

caption: Tremolite
descrip: A medium-sized sample of white tremolite. Crystal formation is linear and flaky. Vitreous in luster.

caption: Tremolite
descrip: Small sample of clear and brown tremolite crystals in marble. Crystals are well formed, prismatic, and vitreous in luster. Small, white natrolite crystals also seem to be present.

caption: Tremolite
descrip: Small sample of white tremolite. Crystals are white, linear, and vitreous in luster.

caption: Quartz
descrip: A baseball-sized sample of quartz. One label calls it "corn cob quartz". Several well-formed, hexagonal points. Many smaller, less-formed crystals surround. Vitreous in luster, clear to white in color.

caption: Green tourmaline
descrip: Small rock with several linear crystal samples of green tourmaline (elbaite). Crystals are dark green and vitreous in luster.

caption: Beryl
descrip: A medium-sized pegmatite sample, dominated almost entirely by a large, well-formed beryl crystal. Crystal is linear, hexagonal, light green, and of vitreous luster.

caption: Cordierite
descrip: Small sample of cordierite in a small, unidentified rock. Luster is vitreous, and crystals are greyish-white to colorless.

caption: Beryl
descrip: Six samples of beryl, varying in size. Crystals are fairly well-formed, light green in color and vitreous in luster.

caption: Beryl
descrip: Sixteen beryl samples of roughly the same size. (about 0.25"x0.5"x0.25"). Luster is vitreous. Color varies from characteristic pale greenish-yellow to rusty orange.
dimnotes: Sixteen samples of roughly the same size. Some are a bit longer in one dimension, but most are about 0.25"x0.5"x0.25".

caption: Tourmaline
descrip: Seven samples of varying size and type of tourmaline. Present are green elbaite variety in quartz in feldspar and quartz, as well as dark grey to black schorl variety. Most of the crystals are well-formed and small in comparison to the rock samples they'

caption: Schorl
descrip: Dark grey schorl variety of tourmaline. Luster is vitreous.

caption: Beryl
descrip: A medium-sized rock with several small samples of golden beryl. One very pronounced sample seems to have had a section removed. Other minerals present include mica and tourmaline.

caption: Kyanite
descrip: Two medium-sized samples of kyanite, or cyanite. Very pale blue in color, pearly in luster. Flaky like a mica.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 0.5"x3"x1"

caption: Essonite
descrip: Essonite or hessonite, a brownish variety of garnet. Crystals are small, vitreous, and characteristically rusty brown.

caption: Kyanite
descrip: Several very small samples of kyanite, or cyanite. Crystals are pale blue, flaky, and pearly in luster.
dimnotes: Most samples are too small to measure. Dimensions correspond to largest sample.

caption: Kyanite
descrip: Baseball-sized rock with large kyanite, or cyanite, streak through it. Crystals are linear, flaky, pale grey-blue, and pearly in luster.

caption: Pyrope + spessartine
descrip: Small rock sample containing pyrope and spessartine. Pyrope is formed in a handful of tiny, dark crystals. Crystals are dark red and vitreous in luster. Spessartine are very small crystals, orange, and vitreous in luster.

caption: Datolite
descrip: Baseball-sized sample of numerous datolite crystals. Crystals are short, but well-formed and vitreous in luster. Crystals are characteristically very pale green. Marked "'george' written on wrapping paper."

caption: Staurolite + garnet
descrip: Two medium-sized samples of staurolite and garnet. Staurolite is isolated in small crystals which are subvitreous in luster and rusty brown. Garnet dominates both samples, in a very dark red to black variety of the usually-red mineral. Garnet is vitreous
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 1"x2"1.75"

caption: Almandine
descrip: Medium-sized sample of almandine, or almandite, garnet. Crystals are dark purple in color, and vitreous in luster. Roughly ten crystals present in a rock of unidentified type. Rock is greasy in luster and dark silver in color.

caption: Datolite
descrip: Two samples of well-formed, pale green datolite. Crystals are tiny, numerous and vitreous in luster.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond with larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 1.25"x1.5"x2"

caption: Kyanite
descrip: Two large samples of rock containing linear kyanite crystals. Crystals are pale blue, well-formed, and vitreous in luster.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 1.5"x3.25"x3

caption: Grossularite
descrip: Two large samples of grossularite, a variety of essonite, which, in turn, is a variety of garnet. Crystals are rusty orange, small, numerous, and vitreous in luster.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 2.5"x3.25"4"

caption: American alligator skull
descrip: American alligator skull cast, separated into top and lower jaw. No marking or identification.

caption: American alligator skull
descrip: American alligator skull cast. Separated into top and lower jaw. Lower jaw is split into halves vertically. No marking or identification.

caption: White tailed deer skull
descrip: White tailed deer skull cast. No marking or identification.

caption: Cobaltite
descrip: Three small samples of cobaltite. Crystals are dark-grey-blue, not very well formed, and metallic in luster. The largest of the three is marked "202".
dimnotes:
Three samples, listed in descending order by size.

1) 0.5"x1"x1"
2) 0.5"x0.5"x0.5"
3) 0.5"x0.5"x0.5"

caption: Pyrite
descrip: A small sample of pyrite in a dark, multilayered rock mass. Pyrite crystals are small and many are distinctly edged, with square formations. Metallic in luster.

caption: Pyrrhotite
descrip: A large sample of pyrrhotite, also known as iron sulfide. Crystals are very small, dense, and formed in thin plates. Metallic in luster.

caption: Scheelite
descrip: Small patterns of scheelite on a medium-sized, small-quartz-dominated rock. Crystals are orange, small, and not very well-formed. Scheelite is an ore of tungsten and is known to fluoresce bright blue under UV rays. Vitreous in luster.

caption: Goethite
descrip: Medium-sized sample of goethite. Crystals appear in needle-like formations about a quarter-inch in diameter. Sample is charcoal-colored and dull in luster. Marked "17", as is the tray container the sample sits in.

caption: Hematite
descrip: A medium-sized sample of red and grey hematite. Crystals are very small, not very well-formed, and dull in luster.

caption: Manganocolumbite
descrip: Medium-sized sample of manganocolumbite, the manganese-heavy variety of columbite. Crystals are tiny, forming thin plates. Luster is submetallic. Rock also contains feldspar. Marked "Very rare" on identification tag.

caption: Goethite
descrip: A medium-sized sample of goethite. Crystals are rounded and formed into numerous round nodules and bubbles, ranging in size from miniscule to a half inch in diameter. Crystals are a shiny, metallic dark silver color, and are metallic in luster.

caption: Fluorite
descrip: Two samples of pale-blue-green fluorite. Crystals are vitreous in luster, well-formed, and very numerous. In both the large and small sample, the fluorite acts as the host mineral for quartz and what appears to be galena.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to the large sample. Small sample:

2) 1"x1"x1"

caption: Calcite
descrip: A small, but nearly entirely homogenous sample of calcite. Crystals are very well-formed, pointed, and hexagonal. Crystals are vitreous in luster and orange-yellow. Marked "93".

caption: Calcite
descrip: Large sample of grey to offwhite calcite crystals. Most of the crystals are jagged, forming multi-direction ridges across the sample. Crystals are vitreous in luster, but also pearly in luster at cleavage points.

caption: Barite + malachite
descrip: Barite and malachite samples on a softball-sized rock. In the matrix, quartz and calcite are also present. Barite crystals are colorless and pearly in luster. Malachite is characteristically forest green, small, vitreous in luster, and spread out in the

caption: Siderite
descrip: A medium-sized sample of siderite in a rock also containing quartz. Siderite is brown, linear, and pearly in luster. Many faces and linear formations present.

caption: Siderite
descrip: Two medium-sized samples of siderite. Crystals range from dark to light brown. All have a pearly luster, especially on large faces. Quartz also present, especially in the larger sample which has large quartz streaks.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 1.25"x1.75"x1.75"

caption: Siderite
descrip: Two medium-sized samples of siderite. Crystals range from dark brown and grey to light brown. All have a pearly luster, especially on large faces. Quartz also present.

caption: Siderite
descrip: Baseball-sized sample of siderite. Crystals range from dark brown to grey, and are pearly in luster.

caption: Malachite
descrip: Medium-sized sample of malachite. Crystals are characteristically green, small, and not very well-formed. Vitreous luster. Barite also present.

caption: Barite + malachite
descrip: Two samples of barite and malachite. Barite crystals are white, tabular and vitreous in luster. Malachite is green, small, dull in luster and massive in habit. Quartz vein also present in both samples. Both are marked "13".
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 2"x4"x"3

caption: Barite + malachite
descrip: Barite and malachite in a medium-sized rock also containing a quartz vein. Barite crystals are white to colorless and form right on top of the quartz vein. Barite luster is vitreous. Malachite is dark green, sparse, and vitreous.

caption: Malachite
descrip: A medium-sized sample of malachite on an oxidized-iron-heavy rock. Malachite is dark to pale green, depending on the position of the massive formation. Malachite crystals have formed around the mamillary formations of the rock underneath.

caption: Barite
descrip: Medium-sized, square sample of barite. Tabular, light brown crystals with perfect cleavage and a pearly luster.

caption: Barite
descrip: Nine samples of barite, of varying size. Colored from white to faint orange, reflecting the oxidize iron-heavy bits present on some samples. Habit is somewhat of a combination of lamellar and coxcomb. Luster is pearly.

caption: Barite
descrip: Two large samples of barite. Crystals are white to rusty orange, reflecting high oxidized-iron content. Habit is lamellar and coxcomb, with fibrous and filiform sections, as well. Luster is pearly.
dimnotes:
Dimensions correspond to larger sample. Smaller sample:

2) 2"x3.5"x3"

caption: Autunite
descrip: Small, sparse collections of tiny, vitreous Autunite crystals. Pale yellow-green in color around the outside, with the actual crystals being radioactive green. Crystals are so small, they're not visible to the naked eye in the photograph. According to th
dimnotes:

2) 1.25"x3"x2.25"

caption: Pearly nautilus shell
descrip: Medium-sized complete shell of the pearly nautilus. Shell is offwhite with burnt-orange stripes.

caption: Pearly nautilus shell
descrip: Medium-sized hemishell of a pearly nautilus. Shell is halved to show the camarae (chambers) in a logarithmic spiral.

caption: Fluted clam shell
descrip: Fluted clam hemishell. Scutes on clam's offwhite surface are about 3/4 inch in diameter.
habitat: Shallow marine epifaunal stationary suspension feeder, reef

caption: Tiger cowry shell
descrip: Baseball-sized , complete, tiger cowry shell. Despite name, shell is spotted, not striped.

descrip: Six common sand dollars of varying diameters and colors. Contained in a plastic baggie marked "common sand dollar" and "bag #2".

caption: Tubed turbine shell
descrip: Medium-sized tubed turbine shell. Coloration is white to faint orange up the spiral. Pronounced fluted edge at the bottom. Interior is iridescent white.

caption: Screw shell
descrip: Long, thin screw shell. Coloration is dark brown at base to white at tip. Tip is chipped slightly.

caption: Spider conch shell
descrip: Large spider conch shell. Six hollow digitations on the outer lip. Upward flaring points to female gender. Coloration is brown to white.

caption: Ramose murex shell
descrip: Medium-sized ramose murex shell. Coloration is mostly white to brown. Entire shell has pronounced spines and scutes. Outer lip of aperture colored pink.

caption: Snipe's bill murex shell
descrip: Small snipe's bill murex shell. Long, thin siphonal canal. Coloration is white with dark brown and grey horizontal stripes. Pink around the outer lip.

caption: Adusta murex shell
descrip: Small adusta murex shell. Coloration is white to burnt brown. Pink around aperture.

caption: Lightning whelk shell
descrip: Four medium-sized knobbed whelk shells. Coloration is white to light brown. Aperture is white. Spikes have been worn down to knobs. Contained in a plastic baggie marked "lightning whelk" and "4 shells".
dimnotes: Four shells are all about the same dimensions.

caption: Lightning whelk
descrip: Small knobbed whelk shell. Coloration is white to brown, aperture is white. Spikes around the spire have worn down to knobs.

caption: True tulip shell
descrip: Medium-sized true tulip shell. Coloration consists of several varying shades of light brown. Symmetrical rows of thin lines spiral along the whorls. Aperture is white.

caption: Tawny murex shell
descrip: Medium-sized tawny murex shell. Coloration is very pale brown to white. Spiky protrusions and scutes cover the entire shell. Aperture is pink.

caption: Chiragra spider conch
descrip: Medium-sized chiragra spider conch shell. Coloration is white to brown. Characteristically long, curved digitations. Grooved, lirate dark brown aperture.

caption: Chiragra spider conch
descrip: Medium-sized chiragra spider conch shell. Coloration is white to brown. Characteristically long, curved digitations. Grooved, lirate dark brown aperture.

caption: Lettered cone shell
descrip: A baseball-sized lettered cone shell. Shell is white with a brown fleck pattern. Aperture is white.

caption: Strawberry top shell
descrip: Small strawberry top shell. White and brown with red markings on the first few whorls. Iridescent aperture.

caption: Florida crown conch shell
descrip: A medium-sized Florida crown conch shell. Coloration is white with stripes of light and dark brown. Scutes on spire point toward apex, and scutes near the base radiate outward. Aperture is white.

caption: Florida crown conch shell
descrip: A medium-sized Florida crown conch shell. Coloration is white with stripes of light and dark brown.  Sharp scutes on spire point toward apex. Aperture is white and brown.

caption: Giant atlantic pyram shell
descrip: Giant atlantic pyram shell. Despite the name, shell is quite small. Orange, blue, yellow and black horizontal stripes around the whorls. Aperture is grey-blue fringed with white.

caption: Smooth top shell
descrip: Very small, penny-sized smooth top shell. Flatly-spiraled whorls, very iridescent and thin.

caption: Florida cone shell
descrip: Small Florida cone shell. Coloration is white with light orange markings. Spire is short and fairly blunt. Orange aperture.

caption: Fighting conch shell
descrip: Medium-sized fighting conch shell. Coloration is white to brown, most of the shell is light orange. Knobby shoulders and a notched lower outer lip. Aperture is brown and lirate.

caption: Chiragra spider conch shell
descrip: Small, seemingly battered chiragra spider conch shell. This shell is more worn down than the others of its type, the digitations being thinner and less well-formed. Aperture is white with brown liration.

caption: Mushroom coral shell
descrip: Medium-sized mushroom coral shell. White, radial, and largely undamaged.
habitat: Shallow marine reef epifaunal stationary suspension feeder

caption: Mushroom coral shell
descrip: Large, white mushroom coral shell. Shell is radial and nearly entirely intact.

caption: Stellar coral shel
descrip: Softball-sized stellar coral. It is offwhite, porous, and mostly intact. Corallites are easily identifiable.
habitat: Shallow marine reef intermediate level epifaunal suspension feeder, colonial

caption: Lace coral shell
descrip: Medium-sized lace coral. Shell is bone white and largely intact. Several corallites showing.
habitat: Marine epifaunal stationary suspension feeder, colonial

caption: Tusk shell
descrip: Long, thin tusk shell. Coloration is faded white. Inside/aperture also white.

caption: Tusk shell
descrip: Long, thin tusk shell. Coloration is faded white. Inside/aperture also white.

caption: Giant atlantic pyram shell
descrip: Giant atlantic pyram shell. Despite the name, shell is quite small. Orange, blue, yellow and black horizontal stripes around the whorls. Aperture is grey-blue fringed with white.

caption: Lettered olive shell
descrip: Four lettered olive shells of almost exactly the same size. Aperture coloration matches outside coloration. Small, dull spires.
dimnotes: Four shells are almost exactly the same dimensions.

caption: Datolite
descrip: Large sample of datolite. Crystals are varying in size, from very tiny to half-inch massive formations. Luster is vitreous, color is clear to white.
